coreInfo.description: Client APP sends request to Generate file based on GROUP ID. Which is just the name of a report.
Client App will receive the Status endpoint where it can ask for status often.
Client App can keep asking for the current status while the job is running.
At one point, the status will be COMPLETED and the response will include the endpoints to download files.
The app can request the files from the endpoints it received in the previous response.
Talend will trigger the Job Execution, creating a Job Execution ID and setting the status to "In Progress"

coreInfo.description: For the long term, it is better to extract data from databases and transform it via Talend

After extracting data the Talend job will create a file, and store it in AWS S3. It will return the mechanism to retrieve the file to the FHIR app. Where is this path? In MongoDB? How can it be retrieved with the FHIR Gateway?

coreInfo.label: ONC Reference Diagram
coreInfo.description:
This diagram shows our representation of our understanding of the FHIR reference architecture. FHIR specification defines a standard for health care data exchange. That means, it defines the services a system must provide, the data structures that must be interchanged, and the security mechanisms that must be put in place before data exchange occurs.
The specification only dictates the interfaces between data provider systems, Carelogic in our case, and Client applications and leaves any internal implementation details to the service providers.
This high-level reference diagram shows in the FHIR Defined Services box (light yellow) the components that will be used to provide such interfaces while showing other components/capabilities required to implement those interfaces.

coreInfo.label: Patient
coreInfo.description: Any person whose data is being stored in CareLogic and wants to retrieve it via external web or mobile apps.

coreInfo.label: Staff
coreInfo.description: Main user of CareLogic, but in this context, it is the user of External Systems that want to communicate with CareLogic through FHIR APIs

coreInfo.label: PingOne
coreInfo.description: Is our IDP provider as a service. It will manage user credentials and a registry of allowed third party apps.

coreInfo.label: Kong Gateway
coreInfo.description: It is our API Gateway. It is responsible for making sure only authenticated requests can access the backend APIs

coreInfo.label: Domain Services
coreInfo.description: These are existing services that already provide the data needed for FHIR services but do not adhere to the specification. They will be reused / consumed so that the data provided will be transformed into FHIR entities by our new System.

coreInfo.label: External Systems
coreInfo.description: Any Third-Party application that will consume our APIs. This can be added on-demand as long as they adhere to the FHIR R4 spec. It represents any system that our customer use / own and want to integrate with CareLogic.

coreInfo.label: Third Party Auth
coreInfo.description: It is an optional module inside CareLogic to allow System Admins to register third-party applications on-demand, without Operations intervention.

coreInfo.label: Patient Access
coreInfo.description: It is an optional module inside CareLogic to allow Staff members to create Patients user accounts on-demand, without Operations intervention.

coreInfo.label: Patient Portal
coreInfo.description: It is an optional module that can be used by Patients to see their own data. It would be a FHIR client application provided by Qualifacts.

coreInfo.label: External Apps
coreInfo.description: Any Third-Party application that will consume our APIs. This can be added on-demand as long as they adhere to the FHIR R4 spec. It is any app the Patient wants to use to retrieve its own data.

coreInfo.label: CareLogic
coreInfo.description: It is Qualifacts main system and while it is not truly in the scope of our project, the Patient Access module and the Third Party Auth module should be built inside the Carelogic system when prioritized.

coreInfo.label: Standalone Apps
coreInfo.description: It is any app that can be used to consume the FHIR APIs and present it to the Patient user. This app must be registered in our system as "allowed" to consume our FHIR APIs.

coreInfo.label: Domain Services
coreInfo.description: Any existing functionality that can be reused and consumed to retrieve data and eventually transformed into FHIR entities.

coreInfo.label: Patient Data
coreInfo.description: It is any data store from which we can extract the required Patient data.

coreInfo.label: Bulk Data Processing
coreInfo.description: This component will implement any bulk data processing requirements. According to the spec, an external system could ask to "dump" the whole list of patients.

coreInfo.label: Patient
coreInfo.description: Is the user that retrieves its own data by using a web app or mobile app. This user must login and grant consent to the standalone app before retrieving any data.

coreInfo.label: External System
coreInfo.description: Any system or application that belongs to our customers and wants to access our data through the FHIR APIs in an unattended way, that is, without the intervention of users. This app will consume the bulk data APIs to retrieve data through text files.

coreInfo.label: API Gateway
coreInfo.description: While FHIR does not define explicitly an API Gateway, it does require capabilities best implemented by such component. The API Gateway will be in charge of being the single entry point for external apps to access our FHIR APIs and will make sure that requests are authenticated before upstreaming requests to the back-end services as required by the spec.

coreInfo.label: IAM Services
coreInfo.description: FHIR requires the use and extension of OpenID Connect and OAuth2 and also requires a component that provides a mechanism for registering Apps and Users and authenticating them while issuing tokens. We must be able to support Authorization Code flows and Client Credentials flow with Client Assertion JWT.

coreInfo.label: FHIR Services
coreInfo.description: This is the component that will expose the rest endpoints that adhere to the FHIR Specification. It will provide Synchronous interfaces for retrieving data about a single patient and Asynchronous services following the bulk data pattern when external systems ask for a list of patients.

coreInfo.label: File Repository
coreInfo.description: When an external system asks for a report containing a list of patients (asynchronous services), the provider system must generate a text file that can later be downloaded by the external system. This c component will store the generated file temporarily until it was downloaded by the external system.

coreInfo.label: Edge Services
coreInfo.description: This component will ensure data in transit is encrypted using TLS 1.2
